segments.text: Of course, I didn't know him at that time, but there's so many people here you mention.
Tiger Teague, we were in the hospital together at Temple, McCloskey General Hospital, and I always liked him very much.
He was, Tiger was in a wheelchair at that time, and I was in bed and then in a wheelchair,
He was already politicking, working hard at it.
And we kept up a relationship, and he used to come to Laredo once in a while on a junket.
There would be a, it was a paper company, I've forgotten what the name of it was, but
had bought a ranch right outside of Laredo and used it for hunting mostly and mainly entertaining.
And the fellow that ran the, ran their lobbying process was a fellow named Ollie Crawford.
Ollie was also a pilot and they had a big plane and he'd bring,
Well one night he had the power of the United States House there in my place.
He had Tiger and Carl Albert and I can't think of many of them, but a bunch of them in there one night.

told him i said damn tiger i said i hope nobody bombs this place with all this but he was a nice fella he was a nice and tiger's nickname came from his uh unwillingness to give up wasn't he a a tireless
person?
Oh, yes, he would.
But I can't say where the nickname came from.
To me, it was Tiger D. Yeah, because I think it was because he was always like a little tiger, always going after it giving a second effort.
He didn't he wouldn't take no for an answer.
All right, back in those months before you left, what did you when you were going to have a good time?
What did you and your buddies do?
as Aggie students?
Well, I had a very good friend named Phil Beckley.
Phil was in my outfit.
He was a year ahead of me.
And another fellow named Ray Youngblood was in the outfit.
We had a lot of fun just going down to Hard Liquors and having a little beer and singing a lot.
At Hard Liquors in that era, was there any check on who was 18 or 21?
Was there any age?
I never had anybody ask me and God only knows if you'd see some pictures of me at that age, you'd think I was 14.
I never had anybody ask me anything.
Did he put up with anybody that got bothersome if they drank too much?
I never saw anybody out of line that ordered liquors.
I'm not saying somebody didn't get a little boisterous or something like that, but as far as really causing any trouble, I never saw it.
And normally you all walked down there?
Oh, yes.
Normally we walked everywhere.
And it would seat about how many?

i don't know but it sure wasn't very big two dozen oh yeah something like that i guess and uh what other what else was available other than things to drink well could you get a hamburger or a hot dog you could uh yeah you'd get a hamburger and uh once in a while they play a little dominoes something like that no dancing no not to mine i don't ever don't remember see it any the only dancing we had right
Round there was, we had dances once in a while down at the, they built this place down near the end of the drill field.
They called it the Grove or something like that.
Outdoors.
Yeah.
And dances there, but our big dances were always at Sabeasa.
Describe those big dances.
Well, they were great really.
The girls would come in, and a few people had dates.

They'd usually, from TSAW, the girls would usually be a couple of busloads, them come down, and then girls would descend from everywhere, it seemed like, and we'd usually, since there wasn't, oh, there was a couple of hotels in Bryan,
I've forgotten the names of them.
LaSalle.
LaSalle and then right across the street the Kentuckian or something like that.
And that was it.
And then a lot of the local people would rent a room out to a girl or what we'd always do is take one dormitory usually and vacate it.
the girls would take over the dormitory.
Of course, everybody left them notes.
But anyway, the dances would be, they'd really be great, because we'd have good bands and have good music.

Now, speaking of the Aggieland, I remember one time we had a band down there, I don't remember what it was, but it was supposed to have been a pretty good band, and there was going to be such a crowd,
that they had them playing in the main area and the Aggieland played over in another area of the deal.
Of Sabeasa?
And let me tell you something.
Before long, they should have moved them around because everybody was over dancing to the Aggieland instead of the big band.
No, they had a great orchestra.
And how did Aggies behave at those dances?
Very well.
You know, I've always, people talk about a bunch of rough boys and everything like that.
As long as the occasions called for it, Aggies were always perfect gentlemen.
They really were.
And I understand the girls loved coming to an Aggie dance, that they were treated like queens.
Oh, yeah, because, my God, you know,
Well, it was only normal.
You'd take guys that hadn't been around a girl in a month or two, and then for the girls to be outnumbered at least two and a half to one or three to one, that was quite a thing, too.
I've heard, did y'all refer to the Bryan 200?
I've heard some people refer to a select group of Bryan girls.
Yes.
There was a few of them.
It was, as I remember, there was only about, there hadn't been more, but there was only about four or five gals that I remember that were from Bryan, and I couldn't call their names offhand.
If I could, I wouldn't.
But they used to,
used to come out there quite a bit.
Johnny Lawrence was from Bryan.
Johnny was two or three classes ahead of me, and I'm trying to think who else was from Bryan there.
Johnny's the only one I remember offhand, one of the boys.
And as we're talking about the students then, summarize generally the basic attitudes of Aggies at the time of the beginning of World War I.
Not the war, but where did Aggie students come from?
Were they liberal, conservative?
What were their values?
Well, when I went to A&M, I was
I was thinking that I'm going to run into basically agricultural people.
Well, it wasn't to this point that there were a lot of them, but there was a lot of boys that were as we'd have called city boys there, too.
A lot of Dallas people, a lot of Houston people, and a lot of West Texas
people.
I would say not about 95% conservative or more, if that's possible.
There were a few very liberal people, but not a lot.
I mean, it was a, the majority of the students
Well, the majority of the people in the state of Texas at that time had come from families that had been hard-pressed.
I don't mean they'd been starving, but they'd been hard-pressed to make ends meet and maintain the home values that they wanted and so on and so forth.
You just had an overall attitude like that there.
I have to lay it on the line and tell you that I, as far as a education book-wise, I didn't get what I went to A&M to get in that respect.
Not because of the school, but because of me.
But I'm going to tell you that I got something at A&M which was an abiding friendship with some of the greatest people.
How did that develop?
Why did it develop?
I don't know.
I guess it's just there was a certain cohesiveness there, and different people, we just gravitated to each other.
And like Ned Bruin, for instance.
Ned is a close friend of mine.
Ned died last year.
Dickie was one of Mr. Heap's boys, Herman Heap.
And Minnie Bell, she was a nice lady.
Let's see, was Fort Albright and John Lindsay, were they in your?
Oh, I knew John well.
Ford was another year ahead, and I didn't really, I knew Ford, but you know who, people didn't know a freshman much if you're junior.
But I knew John Lindsey quite well.
I remember when, after the war, I got to know, we, all of these people, mostly we met at A&M.
And we established a basis, but we became closer friends after the war.
But that was the bond that kept us all together.
How does that bond get initiated?
Who was it made the statement?
I thought I was going to remember that when I heard it.
It says, I can't explain the Aggie spirit.
And if it has to be explained to you, you don't know what it is.
I mean, it's just, I don't know what it is.
But this was even more than that.
I say more than that.
What's more than that?
I just developed some ties with people that were as strong or stronger than blood ties.
And I wouldn't, you know, we're not getting any younger, but I wouldn't take anything for those
those ties that developed and were nurtured over the years and so on and so forth.
In 1941 and two and three, in that period, in the student body, were there some Protestants and some Catholics and some Jewish?
There were all kinds.
I'd be guilty if I said I never heard anybody make a slighting remark.
Sure I did.
But generally, there was not a, there was no put down because you happened to be a Catholic or a Protestant or a Jew or whatever.
And were there Hispanic youngsters, Mexican-American?
We had some there.
It was very, very small, very small.
However, that was probably the largest ethnic group other than Anglo was Hispanic.
But even at that time, it was quite large.
Of course, there were no blacks at that time.
And were you all conscious of each other's family wealth?
No, that was one of the great things about A&M.
That uniform was a great equalizer.
No one, you got to liking a fella because of what he was, not because of what he had or what, for the most part you didn't know what he had.
sure couldn't tell by their clothes because they were all wearing the same thing.
What were the most respected student organizations?
Band, Ross Volunteers, what?
Ross Volunteers was always respected.
The band, but I would

I think the individual outfits, everybody had a certain binding to their individual outfits and not only that to their, if it wasn't to their battery, it was to say the field artillery, the coast artillery or something like that.
Was there any outfit that everybody on the campus agreed was the best or the worst?
It had to be a good outfit with E Battery Field, and the reason I say that, they would tell everybody that.
And they were a good outfit.
It was a San Antonio outfit.
Dang near everybody in it was from San Antonio.
They kept it that way, and they had a good outfit.
Wasn't as good as eye battery, but you know.
There you go.
Let's see.
The most prestigious student office was what?
The individual student.
At the time I was there, I'd say cadet colonel.
That's what I assumed.
And there was a senior class president.
Yes, yes, there were every class had their.
However, as I remember, we gave not much credence to
freshman class president, sophomore class president, so on and so forth.
And when it got on down to senior class president, that's something else.
The editor of the battalion was, you know, something.
Different things like that.
I would say the president of the senior class was a very
High honor.
Head yell leader?
Head yell leader.
But not, head yell leader wouldn't look, well, yes, but that's not as much as it is today, I don't think.
Were you and your buddies aware of any secret fraternities in those days?
Yes, sir.
I'm not going to say anything else about that.
Okay, all right.
Most of the people that I have asked about it indicate that they weren't aware then and aren't aware now.
And sometimes they smile and sometimes they don't.
Because I have the impression that at least one of those organizations goes back maybe 100 years.
But I don't know.
I'm not.
No, I hear you.
I hear you.
Let's see.
The routine of your courses changed in the summer of 42 when you all go to a trimester.
Right.
And so you just stayed there and started taking sophomore courses.
That's correct.
And the core activities continued through that summer.
Correct.
Did everything become more serious?
Yes, sir.
It did.
Because everybody...
I don't want this to sound like nobody wanted to go to service, but everybody was as practical as you could be about something like that.
They wanted to get as much of the schooling behind them as they could.
And it was easier to do it as much as you could then.
If you didn't keep the grades, you were going out immediately, which we had happened to a lot of friends.
Now, as it turned out, I tore a bunch of those guys that went out and then came back and became great successes.
Well, he had told me about how his grades were awful, but the service made him serious and changed him forever.
Did you stay with your pre-med major?
Yes, sir, while I was in school.
However, I have to give you this however, my main deal by this time was just to stay in school.
See, for me, the Korean War is exactly the same.
To put it off, if I could, and at least graduate.
All right, then, when do you leave permanently for the active duty?
Let's see.
I'm trying to think when we went out in 43, I guess it was.
In 43, early 43, they sent us, that's when they sent us to Fort Sill for a basic training
And we go through a 21-week basic training, and then they sent us back to College Station.
Now, we went to Sill.
Some boys went to Camp Roberts, California.
Some to Mineral Wells, to Camp Walters.
I don't know where else they were.
sent possibly one other place.
And then we all came back to school, supposedly for a very short time, but we didn't know.
And we finished one semester of our junior year.
and started the second one and that's when they pulled us out and through which when my group went back to Fort Sill and then to Fort Benning.
Describe how y'all learned you were leaving.
How much lead time did they give you?
What did you take?
As I remember it, not very much.
If you want to count the rumors and how many times we didn't leave, there's a lot of that.
But when it came down to actual leaving, very little lead time.
And what did you take with you?
What you could put in an A bag and a B bag.
And what did you leave here or leave at College Station?
I didn't leave much because I didn't have anything there.
By this time, it had already become a foregone conclusion that we were going.
It was just a question of when.
So no car?
No, I had no car by then, you know.
In fact,
When I was, when I was there at school, we had two parking lots on the campus.
They were both, you know, just open air like, one over by what's now the Triple A building over there.
There was one back there that maybe, maybe you could put 35 cars in it, and then one over behind the dorm,
11, which is the band dorm up in that area, one up there that would have probably held, probably held 100 cars if there would have been enough to fill it, but neither one of them were full.
And that's all the cars on campus, student cars on campus.
Do you recall your feelings or the others' feelings as y'all got on the train to leave?
Well, I think there was a lot of put on for show.
I can only really speak for myself, but I think I'm speaking for
a lot of people, we were very concerned about what's going to happen.
Where are we going to go?
What's going to happen to us?
And so on and so forth.
But nobody's going to come out and say these kind of things.
You know, that wouldn't, that wouldn't be the manly thing to do.
And we're all talking about how we're going to do this and do that.
But
Yes, there's a lot of apprehension on everybody's part.
How did, when you all were at these brief stops at Fort Sill and so forth, how did Aggies compare in their training performance with students from the other colleges?
This is going to sound very braggadocious, but it's the truth.
It's the truth.
There was no one had to
No one had that kind of training, none.
We, at Fort Sill, we had non-coms up there that were practically all inferior in training to what all of our group was.
Did the commissioned officers give you all
praise and credit?
Well, let's say this, they, they, they knew what was going on, but we made, we could make them look good, or we could make them look awful bad.
And I think, to tell you the truth, I think the junior grade officers were a little intimidated by the NM boys.
All right, and in class were you yet a senior?
No, no, we never, none of our group ever got to be seniors.
Okay, all right.
We were just barely juniors.
So, all right, so you hadn't been through final review except as a freshman or sophomore?
We never, let's see.
We went through a final review of sorts when we were freshmen because it wasn't a real deal even then because the seniors our freshman year were taken out of school a little bit early.
Now let's see, but you had been to Silver Taps.
Yes, and that...
Describe Silver Taps.
The most impressive ceremony that Texas A&M has.
I can't tell you the depth of feeling I have for Silver Taps.
The first time that I was ever there, I just was...
It was one of the most moving experiences I've ever had.
We all walked to the academic building, in front of the academic building.
No sound, no cigarettes, no nothing.
Everybody's just standing there.
And then you start hearing the bugles.
